    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why GenAI Cost Forecasts Fail"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Traditional software cost forecasting assumes that compute usage grows linearly with user count. GenAI workloads violate this assumption in two ways. First, per-user token consumption varies by orders of magnitude depending on the feature: a one-sentence chat reply consumes 200 tokens; a document-analysis feature consumes 20 000. Second, GenAI adoption curves are not linear \u2014 they follow S-curves driven by feature discovery and trust-building, then plateau as the addressable user base saturates."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Applying a linear growth rate to a nascent GenAI feature produces wildly wrong annual forecasts. The FinOps team needs at least three models in its toolkit \u2014 linear extrapolation for stable mature workloads, S-curve projection for new feature rollouts, and power-law scaling for open-ended LLM workloads where usage grows with the square root of user count as each user generates more content over time."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Usage Growth Forecast Models",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Model 1: Linear Extrapolation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The simplest model: fit a line to the last N months of actual token volume and project forward. This works well for stable, mature workloads where the user base is not growing rapidly and per-user consumption is stable. It systematically underestimates cost during rapid adoption phases and overestimates during saturation."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from __future__ import annotations\nimport datetime\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\n\n@dataclass\nclass MonthlyUsage:\n    year_month:   str    # \"2025-01\"\n    team:         str\n    feature:      str\n    total_tokens: int\n    cost_usd:     float\n\ndef linear_forecast(\n    history:         list[MonthlyUsage],\n    months_ahead:    int,\n    reference_price: float,   # USD per 1K tokens (internal rate)\n) -> list[tuple[str, float]]:\n    \"\"\"Return [(year_month, forecast_cost_usd)] for months_ahead periods.\"\"\"\n    if len(history) < 2:\n        raise ValueError(\"Need at least 2 months of history for linear forecast\")\n    n      = len(history)\n    x_vals = list(range(n))\n    y_vals = [h.total_tokens for h in history]\n    # Least-squares slope and intercept\n    x_mean = sum(x_vals) / n\n    y_mean = sum(y_vals) / n\n    slope  = sum((x - x_mean) * (y - y_mean) for x, y in zip(x_vals, y_vals)) /                      sum((x - x_mean) ** 2 for x in x_vals)\n    intercept = y_mean - slope * x_mean\n\n    last_month = history[-1].year_month\n    y, m = int(last_month[:4]), int(last_month[5:7])\n    results = []\n    for i in range(1, months_ahead + 1):\n        m += 1\n        if m > 12:\n            m  = 1\n            y += 1\n        projected_tokens = max(0, intercept + slope * (n + i - 1))\n        cost             = projected_tokens / 1_000 * reference_price\n        results.append((f\"{y:04d}-{m:02d}\", cost))\n    return results"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Model 2: S-Curve (Logistic Growth)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "New feature rollouts follow a logistic growth curve: slow initial adoption, rapid acceleration as word spreads, then a plateau as the addressable user base saturates. The S-curve model has three parameters: the saturation ceiling (maximum possible monthly token volume), the growth rate, and the midpoint (the month of fastest growth). Fitting these parameters to early adoption data produces a forecast that captures both the acceleration phase and the eventual plateau \u2014 critical for sizing infrastructure and budget."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import math\n\ndef logistic(t: float, L: float, k: float, t0: float) -> float:\n    \"\"\"Logistic function: L / (1 + exp(-k * (t - t0))).\"\"\"\n    return L / (1 + math.exp(-k * (t - t0)))\n\ndef fit_logistic(\n    history: list[MonthlyUsage],\n    saturation_ceiling: int,  # estimated max monthly tokens\n) -> tuple[float, float]:\n    \"\"\"Return (k, t0) via simple grid search over plausible values.\"\"\"\n    L = saturation_ceiling\n    n = len(history)\n    y_vals = [h.total_tokens for h in history]\n    best_error = float(\"inf\")\n    best_k, best_t0 = 0.5, n / 2\n    for k in [0.1, 0.3, 0.5, 0.8, 1.0, 1.5]:\n        for t0 in [i * 0.5 for i in range(1, n * 4)]:\n            error = sum(\n                (y - logistic(t, L, k, t0)) ** 2\n                for t, y in enumerate(y_vals)\n            )\n            if error < best_error:\n                best_error = error\n                best_k, best_t0 = k, t0\n    return best_k, best_t0\n\ndef scurve_forecast(\n    history:            list[MonthlyUsage],\n    months_ahead:       int,\n    saturation_ceiling: int,\n    reference_price:    float,\n) -> list[tuple[str, float]]:\n    k, t0 = fit_logistic(history, saturation_ceiling)\n    n      = len(history)\n    last_month = history[-1].year_month\n    y, m = int(last_month[:4]), int(last_month[5:7])\n    results = []\n    for i in range(1, months_ahead + 1):\n        m += 1\n        if m > 12:\n            m = 1; y += 1\n        projected_tokens = logistic(n + i - 1, saturation_ceiling, k, t0)\n        cost             = projected_tokens / 1_000 * reference_price\n        results.append((f\"{y:04d}-{m:02d}\", cost))\n    return results"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "Estimating the saturation ceiling: "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "The ceiling is the maximum monthly token volume if every eligible user uses the feature at the expected rate. Compute it as: addressable_users \u00d7 activation_rate \u00d7 sessions_per_user_per_month \u00d7 avg_tokens_per_session. If you cannot estimate it, use a conservative ceiling (2\u00d7 current peak) and revisit after three months of adoption data."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Model 3: Power-Law Scaling"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Some GenAI workloads exhibit power-law scaling: each additional user generates more tokens than the previous user, because heavier users adopt the tool later and use it more intensively. This is common in developer copilot tools and AI-assisted research features. The power-law model fits a relationship of the form cost = a \u00d7 users^b, where b > 1 indicates super-linear growth."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import math\n\ndef fit_power_law(\n    user_counts: list[int],    # monthly active users\n    costs:       list[float],  # actual cost USD, same length\n) -> tuple[float, float]:\n    \"\"\"Return (a, b) for cost = a * users^b via log-linear regression.\"\"\"\n    assert len(user_counts) == len(costs) >= 3\n    log_u = [math.log(u) for u in user_counts if u > 0]\n    log_c = [math.log(c) for c, u in zip(costs, user_counts) if u > 0]\n    n     = len(log_u)\n    u_mean = sum(log_u) / n\n    c_mean = sum(log_c) / n\n    b = sum((u - u_mean) * (c - c_mean) for u, c in zip(log_u, log_c)) /                 sum((u - u_mean) ** 2 for u in log_u)\n    a = math.exp(c_mean - b * u_mean)\n    return a, b\n\ndef power_law_forecast(\n    a:            float,\n    b:            float,\n    future_users: list[int],   # projected MAU per month\n) -> list[float]:\n    return [a * (u ** b) for u in future_users]\n\n# Example: if b=1.3, each 10% increase in users drives a 13% cost increase.\n# This means cost grows faster than users \u2014 important signal for capacity planning."
          }
        ]
      },
