      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Ensemble Forecasting"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In practice, a feature transitions through model regimes over its lifetime: S-curve during rollout, power-law during heavy adoption, linear during maturity. An ensemble forecast blends all three models, weighted by the model's recent accuracy on held-out data. This prevents the forecast from being catastrophically wrong when a workload transitions between regimes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass\n\n@dataclass\nclass EnsembleForecast:\n    year_month:       str\n    linear_usd:       float\n    scurve_usd:       float\n    powerlaw_usd:     float\n    ensemble_usd:     float   # weighted blend\n    linear_weight:    float\n    scurve_weight:    float\n    powerlaw_weight:  float\n\ndef ensemble_forecast(\n    linear_forecasts:   list[tuple[str, float]],\n    scurve_forecasts:   list[tuple[str, float]],\n    powerlaw_forecasts: list[tuple[str, float]],\n    # Weights must sum to 1.0; derived from each model's recent MAPE\n    linear_weight:   float = 0.4,\n    scurve_weight:   float = 0.4,\n    powerlaw_weight: float = 0.2,\n) -> list[EnsembleForecast]:\n    assert abs(linear_weight + scurve_weight + powerlaw_weight - 1.0) < 1e-6\n    results = []\n    for (ym, lin), (_, sc), (_, pl) in zip(\n        linear_forecasts, scurve_forecasts, powerlaw_forecasts\n    ):\n        blend = lin * linear_weight + sc * scurve_weight + pl * powerlaw_weight\n        results.append(EnsembleForecast(\n            year_month       = ym,\n            linear_usd       = lin,\n            scurve_usd       = sc,\n            powerlaw_usd     = pl,\n            ensemble_usd     = blend,\n            linear_weight    = linear_weight,\n            scurve_weight    = scurve_weight,\n            powerlaw_weight  = powerlaw_weight,\n        ))\n    return results\n\ndef compute_model_weights_from_mape(\n    linear_mapes:   list[float],\n    scurve_mapes:   list[float],\n    powerlaw_mapes: list[float],\n) -> tuple[float, float, float]:\n    \"\"\"Inverse-MAPE weighting: better models get higher weight.\"\"\"\n    inv = [\n        1 / (sum(linear_mapes)   / len(linear_mapes)   + 1e-9),\n        1 / (sum(scurve_mapes)   / len(scurve_mapes)   + 1e-9),\n        1 / (sum(powerlaw_mapes) / len(powerlaw_mapes) + 1e-9),\n    ]\n    total = sum(inv)\n    return inv[0]/total, inv[1]/total, inv[2]/total"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Forecast Accuracy: Mean Absolute Percentage Error"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Track each model's accuracy on a rolling hold-out: fit the model on months 1 to N-3, forecast months N-2 through N, compare against actuals. The mean absolute percentage error (MAPE) is the primary accuracy metric. A MAPE below 15% is good; above 30% signals the model is wrong for this workload and a different model should take more weight in the ensemble."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def mape(actuals: list[float], forecasts: list[float]) -> float:\n    \"\"\"Mean absolute percentage error. Returns a fraction (0.15 = 15%).\"\"\"\n    assert len(actuals) == len(forecasts) > 0\n    return sum(\n        abs(a - f) / a\n        for a, f in zip(actuals, forecasts)\n        if a > 0\n    ) / len(actuals)\n\ndef rolling_mape_evaluation(\n    history:        list[MonthlyUsage],\n    forecast_fn,    # callable(history, months_ahead, ...) -> [(ym, cost)]\n    hold_out:       int = 3,\n    **kwargs,\n) -> float:\n    train   = history[:-hold_out]\n    test    = history[-hold_out:]\n    preds   = forecast_fn(train, hold_out, **kwargs)\n    actuals = [h.cost_usd for h in test]\n    forecasts = [p[1] for p in preds]\n    return mape(actuals, forecasts)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Scenario Planning: Bull, Base, Bear"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A single-point forecast is not a plan \u2014 it is a best guess that will be wrong. Present forecasts as three scenarios: bear (adoption slower than expected, model optimisations materialise), base (current trend continues), bull (faster adoption, per-request tokens grow as features deepen). Finance teams can use the bear scenario for committed budget and the bull scenario for contingency reserves."
          }
        ]
      },
